<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06141124 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06141124 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  Charles &quot;Chuckie&quot; O'Brien, the foster son of former Teamsters president JamesHoffa, was ordered banned from the union for allegedly associating withorganized crime leaders, a newspaper said.;    The order came from FrederickLacey, a court-appointed union administrator in New York who is attempting torid the Teamsters of influence from organized crime, the Detroit News reportedSunday.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  HOFFA'S FOSTER SON BANNED FROM TEAMSTERS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Lacey's order requires final approval from U.S. District Judge DavidEdelstein in New York. Edelstein presided over the government's 1988anti-racketeering lawsuit against the 1.6 million-member union.;    In hisruling, Lacey upheld four civil charges against O'Brien, who has been workingas an international organizer assigned to the Teamsters' Southern Conferencein Hallandale, Fla.;    Lacey ordered O'Brien banned on a charge of having a&quot;knowing association&quot; with eight reputed Mafia figures in Detroit, thenewspaper said. He said O'Brien acknowledged in a deposition taken in November1988 that he was an acquaintance or friend of all eight.;    O'Brien is one ofthe last people to see Hoffa alive, according to records from an investigationinto Hoffa's disappearance in July 1975. O'Brien repeatedly has deniedknowledge of the circumstances of Hoffa's death.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Detroit  </CITY><EDITION>  Street  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910520  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  May  </MONTH><PG.COL>  6A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  192  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday May 20, 199100141124,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LAN